Dear Governor Purdue:
¬†
I am writing to you today to voice my concern about (and vehement opposition to) the proposed 5% increase in taxes on alcohol in your recent budget proposal.
¬†
You state in your budget summary that "As families and businesses across our state are tightening their belts to make ends meet, government must do the same."¬† However, rather than tighten your belt to fit the budget realities, you have opted to give state government a raise on the backs of those of us who enjoy an occasional beer (and the brewers who make that beer).¬† Can you imagine the reaction of my employer if I were to demand a raise based on a behavior of my boss I didn't particularly approve of?¬† I would (rightfully) be laughed out of the room (if not fired outright).
¬†
The further claim that increasing so-called "sin" taxes is justified to "help offset healthcare costs associated with the use of tobacco products and alcohol" heaps insult upon injury.¬† As you are no doubt aware, scientific studies reaffirm the benefits of moderate alcohol use (in case you are¬†unaware, a handy review of the health benefits of moderate alcohol use can be found here: <http://www2.potsdam.edu/hansondj/alcoholandhealth.html>http://www2.potsdam.edu/hansondj/alcoholandhealth.html).¬† No such claim can be made on behalf of cigarettes, and to lump them together as equal contributors to increased health care costs is to pretend that any user of alcohol is an abuser of alcohol.¬†
¬†
I know pulling an extra $500 million dollars in tax revenue into the state's bucket has to be tempting to any politician (especially when incomes are down so the state's income tax revenue has dropped), but please take a moment to consider what it means for a moderate user of alcohol, for example, someone who drinks one beer nightly with his or her dinner and enjoys the health benefits that result from such moderate use of alcohol.
¬†
One of my personal favorite beers is brewed right here in North Carolina by Highland Breweries.¬† It currently sells for $8.99 a six pack at my local Harris Teeter.¬† Now, admittedly,¬†$8.99 is on the high end for a six pack, but¬†goodness grows in North Carolina, so I think it's worth it.¬† Thanks to your tax increase, that six pack will cost me an extra $.45.¬† Over the course of a year, that's over $23 (for the sake of easy math, I've presumed I drink one a night, but¬†skip Sundays in a nod to the old "blue laws").
¬†
Sure, as you said in your press conference, "those of us who choose to use those two products can afford to suck it up."¬† I can also choose to buy a cheaper beer that's not from NC.¬† Heck, I live in south Charlotte a mere hop, skip and a jump from the state line, so I can choose not to buy any alcohol in NC at all (don't worry, I'll stay under the legal transport limits).¬† But those choices aren't exactly what you had in mind when you mentioned choices, I'm sure.¬†Because those choices, when taken by any significant number of people, would kill several good North Carolina companies that brew wonderful beers, and inflate the South Carolina treasuries at the expense of our own.
¬†
Additionally, beer taxes are a regressive tax, placing a higher burden on those who can afford¬†it least and North Carolina already has one of the most burdensome¬†beer taxes in the entire country (<http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/n_c_has_fourth_highest_beer_tax>http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/n_c_has_fourth_highest_beer_tax).¬†
¬†
I urge you to reconsider compounding this already unfair tax burden in the face of the economic crisis we face (and to certainly not use that crisis as an excuse to ply your tax increase).¬† North Carolina citizens and North Carolina beer drinkers deserve better and are paying attention.

Thank you for your consideration,

Christian Polking
