Subject: FIPP and More at 4

Comment: I am writing to you to let you know how devastating it will be to get rid of the FIPP program and the More at 4 program. I am a parent of a child with autism and these 2 programs are very important in our lives. The truth is there are very few programs that will accept my son. I will admit he can be a handful but the FIPP workers just help me through it and never say a word. Anytime I have needed support for my son FIPP has been there. I have worked with many different people in the organization. Jacob, my son, has received Speech Therapy and Occupational therapy through them. I have had their staff come to my house to help me teach my son. The playgroup that they run gave my son skills to be able to play and also play with other children something I thought would not be possible. If you close down FIPP I have no idea what we will do and what about the children that will be there in the future. Please do not let our budget problems tell our disabled children we do not care about them. Next is the More at 4, we can not cut out this program. At age 3 disabled children no longer receive help from the CDSA. They are placed in the school system where they receive their therapies. The More at 4 program allows these children to be in a school setting and learn what will help them when they go to Kindergarten. They are expected to be able to function in Kindergarten but without any support from More at 4 they will not be able to. That will not only take away from their education but also the education of the other children in their class. My son is now in the More at 4 program. He has learned so much and I think one more year of More at 4 will have him ready to transition into Kindergarten. Being a mom of an autistic son I know what he would be like taking him into Kindergarten. He would shut down for awhile and then meltdown. He has 2 hour long screaming, crying meltdowns. The More at 4 program for him was eased into and now I am able to leave him there with no phone calls about meltdowns. Please do not take this program away from our children, it could be detrimental to our future. They will be the ones in charge of our country one day. Thank You, Lisa Hanlon Concerned Parent of a disabled child

